04277nam a22005415i 9780228007821DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280078217 a10.1515/97802280078212doi  a(DE-B1597)655398  a(OCoLC)1223036404  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHX363.5b.V35 2021 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a335.43094992231 aValiavicharska, Zhivka, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRestless History :bPolitical Imaginaries and Their Discontents in Post-Stalinist Bulgaria /cZhivka Valiavicharska. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b19 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tFigures -- tPost-Stalinism in the Folds of Humanism -- tJourneys of the 1844 Manuscripts: Historiographic Shifts in Marxist Thought -- tGender and Social Reproduction the Socialist Way -- tIn the Darkness of Humanism -- tStalinism to Post-Stalinism: Shifting Histories, Shifting Readings -- tViolent Revivals -- tUncanny Symbioses: Ethnonationalism and the Global Orientations of Bulgarian Socialism -- tIn the Haunted Landscapes of Post-Socialism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPost-Stalinism – the last three decades of socialism in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe – gave birth to new political ideas and social struggles, which reshaped socialist societies and forged new global imaginaries. With a focus on socialist Bulgaria, Restless History traces the dynamic polemical and social shifts that took place during this period.With anti-Stalinist and humanist visions, socialist societies rebuilt their material and social worlds around social-reproductive needs such as care, housing, education, leisure, rest, and access to culture and the arts. In the sphere of global politics, they created anti-racist, feminist, anti-colonial, and anti-imperialist solidarities that challenged Western hegemony and reordered the global geographies of power. Yet the changes of the period also took some troubling directions: humanist imaginaries of socialist progress, modernity, and nationhood welcomed ideas of national and social homogeneity, opening the doors to ethnonationalism. Following the promising as well as troubling moments in the history of Bulgarian post-Stalinism, Zhivka Valiavicharska brings to life the complexities of real lived socialism.Restless History re-examines the post-Stalinist period in Bulgaria, Eastern Europe, and beyond – in all its tensions and contradictions – to offer the socialist past as an unfinished history, one that cannot be easily put to rest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunismxHistory. 0aSocialismzBulgariaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocialismzEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228007821?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007821/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles